# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-indiana-gubernatorial-election] The **1816 Indiana gubernatorial election** took place on August 5, 1816.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Jonathan Jennings, the longtime U.S. delegate representing the Indiana Territory's at-large congressional district and former president of the Indiana constitutional convention, defeated the incumbent territorial governor Thomas Posey.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-indiana-gubernatorial-election] This was the first gubernatorial election held following ratification of the Constitution of Indiana.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-indiana-gubernatorial-election] The short turnaround between the adjournment of the constitutional convention on June 29 and the date of the election left a narrow window for electioneering.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Of the roughly 12,000 eligible voters, more than 9,000 cast ballots for governor, indicating substantial popular interest in the election.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-indiana-gubernatorial-election] The Democratic-Republican Party was dominant nationally following the War of 1812, and the politics of the new state were conducted on a nonpartisan basis.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Jennings and Posey represented political factions held over from the territorial period.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Jennings, a resident of Clark County, was the leader of the antislavery eastern faction, while Posey was associated with the proslavery western faction based out of Vincennes.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Posey, a Federalist and a slaveholder, was unpopular, politically isolated, and too ill to actively campaign.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-indiana-gubernatorial-election] He had opposed the movement for statehood as premature, for which he was accused of seeking to retain his position as the unelected territorial governor.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-indiana-gubernatorial-election] With his residence in Jeffersonville, he was too far from the territorial capital in Corydon to effectively respond to events.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Jennings conducted a campaign typical of the era, speaking to voters directly at log rollings, militia musters, and other public functions, while maintaining the pretense of indifference to his election expected of nineteenth-century candidates.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Posey's surrogates attempted to link Jennings to the recent unpopular congressional salary increase and the non-payment of militiamen during the War of 1812.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Charges that Jennings had pursued statehood against the wishes of the western counties failed to mobilize the electorate against the new constitution.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-indiana-gubernatorial-election] On Election Day, Jennings defeated Posey with strong support from voters in the eastern counties, while Posey performed well in the western part of the state.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-indiana-gubernatorial-election] The original manuscript returns appear to be lost.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Records kept by the Indiana House of Representatives show topline figures for Jennings and Posey, noted above, but omit the county-level data.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Phil Lampi locates complete or partial data for eight out of fifteen counties.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana] The newly created state of Indiana elected its sole member of the U.S.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana] House of Representatives in August 1816, in advance of statehood, to represent Indiana's at-large congressional district.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana] Democratic-Republican William Hendricks was elected with 80.2% of the vote over Allen Thom who received 19.7% of the vote.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana] The state was admitted December 11, 1816 and the new member was admitted on that day to the 14th Congress which would end March 3, 1817.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana] Hendricks was re-elected August 4, 1817 to the 15th Congress.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election-in-indiana] A presidential election was held in Indiana on November 14, 1816 as part of the 1816 United States presidential election.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election-in-indiana] The Democratic-Republican ticket of the U.S. secretary of state James Monroe and the governor of New York Daniel D.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election-in-indiana] Tompkins received three votes from electors chosen by the Indiana General Assembly.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election-in-indiana] The Federalist Party failed to nominate a candidate.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election-in-indiana] Monroe won the national election handily, defeating the senior U.S. senator from New York Rufus King, who received 34 votes from unpledged electors despite not being a candidate.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election-in-indiana] Indiana's right to participate in the election was disputed during the 1817 electoral college vote count.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election-in-indiana] Taylor, the U.S. representative for New York's 11th congressional district, argued that as the resolution recognizing Indiana's admission as the 19th state had not been approved until after the meeting of the electoral colleges, the three votes from Indiana should not be counted.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election-in-indiana] Opinion in Congress overwhelmingly favored counting Indiana's votes.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election-in-indiana] Ingham, the question was postponed indefinitely, and the count proceeded with Indiana's votes included.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-senate-elections-in-indiana] The **1816–17 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-senate-elections-in-indiana] Senate elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-senate-elections-in-indiana] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1816 and 1817, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-senate-elections-in-indiana] In these elections, terms were up for the senators in Class 2.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-senate-elections-in-indiana] The Democratic-Republican Party gained a net of two seats from the admission of a new state.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-senate-elections-in-indiana] In these special and general elections, the winners were seated during 1816 or before March 4, 1817; ordered by election date.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-senate-elections-in-indiana] In these general elections, the winners were seated March 4, 1817; ordered by state.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-senate-elections-in-indiana] All of the elections involved the Class 2 seats.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-senate-elections-in-indiana] In three special elections and two general elections, the winners were elected in 1817 after March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-senate-elections-in-indiana] The new state of Indiana elected its first two senators, both Democratic-Republicans, James Noble and Waller Taylor.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-senate-elections-in-indiana] The election was held November 8, 1816 in advance of Indiana's December 11, 1816 admission as a state.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-senate-elections-in-indiana] In the election legislators cast a single ballot and the first and second place candidates were deemed elected.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-senate-elections-in-indiana] Robert Goodloe Harper won election over John Thomson Mason by a margin of 1.12%, or 1 vote, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-senate-elections-in-indiana] Alexander Contee Hanson won election over William Winder by a margin of 8.24%, or 7 votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-senate-elections-in-indiana] The new state of Mississippi elected its first two senators, both Democratic-Republicans, Walter Leake and Thomas H.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1816-united-states-senate-elections-in-indiana] Two separate elections were held in which each senator was elected.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] The **1816–17 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 30, 1816, and August 14, 1817.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 15th United States Congress convened on December 1, 1817.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] The size of the House increased to 184 after Indiana and Mississippi achieved statehood.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] The Democratic-Republican Party entered the election with a large majority, yet made sizable gains, helping trigger the virtually nonpartisan Era of Good Feelings under new President James Monroe, elected in 1816.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Two major events combined to help eliminate the declining Federalist Party from meaningful contention.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] First, the War of 1812 had concluded in 1815 with a feeling of national pride and relief, with the small American military fighting the much more powerful British forces to a draw punctuated by General Andrew Jackson's dramatic victory at the Battle of New Orleans.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Federalists had opposed the risky but ultimately successful war, with some New England Federalists advocating radical measures at the Hartford Convention.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Second, the 1815 eruption of Mount Tambora in present-day Indonesia, itself the most powerful in recorded history and following other major eruptions, temporarily disrupted global climate.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] The effects severely damaged the agricultural economy of New England, where Federalist support was strongest, causing privation, popular discontent, and mass emigration westward.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Mississippi was admitted as a state in 1817 during the 15th Congress, adding one seat.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] There were special elections in 1816 and 1817 to the 14th United States Congress and 15th United States Congress.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Special elections are sorted by date then district.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Connecticut elected its members September 16, 1816.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Delaware elected its members October 7, 1816.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Georgia elected its members October 7, 1816.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Indiana elected its member August 4, 1817, having just elected him just the year before to the new seat.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Kentucky elected its members August 5, 1816.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Louisiana elected its members July 1–3, 1816.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Maryland elected its members October 6, 1816.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Massachusetts's electoral law required a majority for election.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] In five districts this was not met on the first election, requiring additional trials to be held.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Massachusetts elected its members November 4, 1816.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] District numbers differed between source used and elsewhere on Wikipedia; district numbers used elsewhere on Wikipedia used here.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Mississippi was admitted as a state on December 10, 1817 from the western half of the former Mississippi Territory (the eastern half became Alabama Territory) It elected its first representative to Congress August 4–5, 1817.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] New Hampshire elected its members August 26, 1816.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] In 1816, the Democratic-Republican candidates ran unopposed.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] New Jersey elected its members November 4–5, 1816.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] New York elected its members April 23 to 25, 1816.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] North Carolina elected its members August 14, 1817.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Ohio elected its members October 8, 1816.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p02] Pennsylvania elected its members October 8, 1816.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p02] Rhode Island elected its members August 27, 1816.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p02] South Carolina elected its members October 14–15, 1816.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p02] Tennessee elected its members August 7–8, 1817.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p02] Vermont elected its members September 3, 1816, replacing its six Federalists with six Democratic-Republicans.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p02] Virginia elected its members in April 1817.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p02] There were three territories with the right to send delegates during at least part of the 15th Congress.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p02] Illinois Territory also only existed during the 1st Session, as it was admitted to the Union as the State of Illinois on December 3, 1818.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p02] Mississippi Territory only existed during the first few months of the 15th Congress, but did not elect a delegate, since it was admitted to the Union as a state a few days into the 1st Session of the 15th Congress.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p02] There were two elections held for the delegate from Missouri Territory.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p02] The first was contested by Rufus Easton on the grounds of electoral fraud.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p02] This election was declared void, and a second election was held on August 4, 1817.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1817-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p02] It was won without controversy by John Scott, who took his seat on December 8, 1817.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] The **1818–19 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 26, 1818, and August 12, 1819.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 16th United States Congress convened on December 6, 1819.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] They occurred during President James Monroe's first term.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Also, newly admitted Alabama elected its first representatives in September 1819, increasing the size of the House to 186 seats.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] This election occurred in a politically uneventful period marked by exceptionally low levels of partisan rivalry known as the Era of Good Feelings.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] The weak Federalist Party, with limited influence in few states, no longer effectively opposed the Democratic-Republican Party, which increased its large majority.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Illinois was admitted in 1818, adding one seat.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Alabama and Maine were admitted during the 16th Congress.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] One new seat was added for Alabama, while Maine, splitting from Massachusetts, simply retained its Representatives.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] There were special elections in 1818 and 1819 to the 15th United States Congress and 16th United States Congress.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Connecticut elected its members September 21, 1818.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] The delegation changed from seven Federalists to seven Democratic-Republicans then the retirement of six incumbents and the party-change of the seventh.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Delaware elected its members October 5, 1818.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Georgia elected its members October 5, 1818.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Illinois elected its member August 2, 1819, after the new congress began but before the first session convened.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] The incumbent had just been elected to the new seat in late 1818.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Indiana re-elected its member August 3, 1818.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Kentucky elected its members August 3, 1818.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Louisiana elected its member July 6–8, 1818.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Louisiana held an election for the 16th Congress at the same time that it held a special election to finish the 15th Congress.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Data were only available for the special election, but the general election would presumably have had very similar results, and so the results for the special election are duplicated here.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Maryland elected its members October 5, 1818.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Massachusetts elected its members November 2, 1818.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Massachusetts's electoral law required a majority for election, n Massachusetts's electoral law required a majority for electionMassachusetts's electoral law required a majority for electionecessitating additional elections in five districts on April 5, 1819, and July 26, 1819.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] This was the last election in which the District of Maine — comprising congressional districts 14 through 20 — was part of Massachusetts.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] The District became the State of Maine during the 16th Congress.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Mississippi elected its member August 2–3, 1819, after the new congress began but before the first session convened.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] New Hampshire elected its members March 9, 1819, after the new congress began but before the first session convened.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] New Jersey elected its members October 13, 1818.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] New York elected its members April 28–30, 1818, the earliest of any state.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] At this time, the Democratic-Republicans in New York were divided into two factions, the "Bucktails" who were opposed to Governor Dewitt Clinton's Erie Canal project, led by Martin Van Buren, and on the other side, Clinton's supporters, known as Clintonians.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] In many districts, the remaining Federalists allied with the Clintonians, with candidates running on a joint ticket.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Several candidates who ran under that joint ticket cannot be clearly categorized, and are marked C/F.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Others who ran under the joint ticket are marked by their party with a footnote indicating that they ran under the joint ticket.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] North Carolina elected its members August 12, 1819, after the new congress began but before the first session convened.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Ohio elected its members October 13, 1818.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Pennsylvania elected its members October 13, 1818.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p01] Rhode Island elected its members August 25, 1818.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p02] South Carolina elected its members October 12–13, 1818.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p02] Tennessee elected its members August 5–6, 1819, after the new congress began but before the first session convened.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p02] Vermont elected its members September 1, 1818.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p02] Virginia elected its members in April 1819, after the new congress began but before the first session convened.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-indiana-p02] There were four territories with the right to send non-voting delegates to at least part of the 16th Congress, two of which, Michigan Territory and Arkansas Territory were new to this Congress.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-senate-election-in-indiana] The **1818–19 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-senate-election-in-indiana] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1818 and 1819, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-senate-election-in-indiana] In these elections, terms were up for the senators in Class 3.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-senate-election-in-indiana] The Democratic-Republican Party gained two seats.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-senate-election-in-indiana] The Federalists had only three seats being contested, of which they lost two and the third was left vacant due to a failure to elect.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-senate-election-in-indiana] In these special elections, the winners were seated during 1818 or before March 4, 1819; ordered by election date.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-senate-election-in-indiana] In these general elections, the winner was seated on March 4, 1819 (except where noted due to late election); ordered by state.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-senate-election-in-indiana] All of the elections involved the Class 3 seats.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-senate-election-in-indiana] In these special elections, the winners were seated in 1819 after March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-senate-election-in-indiana] The new Congress was seated December 6, 1819, so some of these late-elected senators were seated after that.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-senate-election-in-indiana] Due to both the Class 3 seat falling vacant at the normal end of the term and the Class 1 seat falling vacant due to the death of Alexander Contee Hanson, the legislature voted for both seats simultaneously.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-senate-election-in-indiana] Edward Lloyd received the most votes and won the Class 3 seat.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1818-united-states-senate-election-in-indiana] William Pinkney received the second-most votes and won the Class 1 seat.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] The **1828 Indiana gubernatorial election** took place on August 4, 1828, under the provisions of the Constitution of Indiana.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] It was the fifth gubernatorial election in the State of Indiana.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Ray, the incumbent governor, was re-elected, defeating Israel T.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Canby, the former state senator representing Jefferson and Jennings counties, and Harbin H.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Moore, the outgoing speaker of the Indiana House of Representatives, in a three-way race.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] The election took place concurrently with races for lieutenant governor and members of the Indiana General Assembly.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Ray won the 1825 Indiana gubernatorial election after succeeding to the governorship upon the resignation of William Hendricks, who had stepped down to accept a seat in the United States Senate.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] From the beginning, his tenure was controversial: opponents alleged Ray was yet shy of the minimum age of thirty years when he took the oath of office, and his ascension as such had been unconstitutional.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] (In fact, Ray turned thirty a few days after his inauguration, but continued to serve as governor regardless.) Following his re-election to a full term in August 1825, Ray attempted to steer a middle course between the emerging Jacksonian and Anti-Jacksonian factions in federal politics.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] His independent stance attracted criticisms from both camps, as did his acceptance of a federal commission in 1826 to negotiate the Treaty of Mississinewas, which appeared to violate the constitutional prohibition against governors serving in federal employ during their tenure in office.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] The General Assembly debated whether Ray had forfeited his office by accepting the commission, and separately, whether he had neglected his duties by absenting himself from the capital for long periods.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Indiana State Treasurer Samuel Merrill attacked Ray publicly, alleging the governor to be "destitute of principle and all sense of propriety," and accusing him of embezzling public funds.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Ultimately, an investigative committee found no evidence of wrongdoing, and a resolution calling for Ray's removal was defeated in the House by a vote of 31 to 27.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] For the first time, presidential politics played a significant role in the gubernatorial election.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] The 1828 United States presidential election pitted President John Quincy Adams against challenger Andrew Jackson four years after Adams narrowly bested Jackson in a hard-fought campaign that had to be decided by the U.S.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Opposition to Ray's re-election abounded as the 1828 election came into view.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] The dispute with Merrill, while acrimonious, remained personal in nature, and failed to mobilize the public against him.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Far more damaging was Ray's studied neutrality in the brewing rematch between Adams and Jackson.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] For the first time since 1816, (when Indiana's electoral votes were awarded by the state legislature,) the presidential and gubernatorial contests would occur in the same year.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Supporters of Adams and Jackson held their presidential preference in mind as they considered the candidates for governor.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Attempting to appeal to both factions, Ray pleased neither.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] His position attracted rivals from across the political spectrum, and Ray had to endure attacks from both Jacksonians and Anti-Jacksonians throughout the campaign.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Ray feared a challenger backed by supporters of President Adams would split the electorate along partisan lines.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] In 1824 he had supported Henry Clay for president but preferred Jackson over Adams in the ensuing contingent election in the House of Representatives.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] While the 1825 gubernatorial election had not been fought along partisan lines, Ray's opponent in that contest, Chief Justice Isaac Blackford, was a known "Adams man." Blackford, Lieutenant Governor John H.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Thompson, and Speaker Moore were each proposed as potential candidates for governor in the winter of 1827–28.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] All three were known to favor Adams in the approaching presidential election; Moore had actually been a delegate to the Adams State Convention in January 1828 that nominated a slate of electors pledged to Adams and adopted a platform defending the policies of the administration.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Thompson was the leading candidate against Ray until early April, when Moore's candidacy began to pick up steam.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] No candidate was ever formally endorsed as the "Adams" or "National Republican" nominee for governor, though Moore's presidential preference was known publicly and remarked on in the strategic considerations of the rival Jacksonians.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Israel Canby emerged as the early favorite among Jacksonians in 1828; a physician and member of the state senate from Madison, he had been a delegate to the Jackson State Conventions of 1824 and 1828.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] When the 1828 convention adjourned, some Jacksonians went away with the understanding that Canby had been nominated for governor.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Canby, however, had determined to withdraw his candidacy for personal considerations.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] In early May, as it became apparent Ray would be opposed in the gubernatorial election by an Adams man, the Jackson State Committee saw fit to approach the governor with the offer of an endorsement.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Ray wrote in reply that the committee could "dispose of me and my name as you in your wisdom see fit," that he would not commit himself to either candidate for president but would nonetheless welcome "the united support of the Jacksonians" in the August election.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] He asked only that Jacksonian support, were it forthcoming, remain private until after the election to avoid any appearance of partisanship.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Subsequent events would cause Canby to re-enter the race in early July with less than a month left in the campaign.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Twelve years after statehood, Indiana was still a frontier state, and enthusiasm for internal improvements was unanimous and bipartisan.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] The Jacksonians sought to make an issue of the upcoming presidential election, which due to the staggered electoral calendar would be held in November, two months after the gubernatorial contest.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Despite intense pressure to declare a preference, Ray remained steadfastly neutral in the presidential contest, decrying the spirit of partisanship endemic in state politics.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Campaigning was conducted, not only by sympathetic editors in the press, but by the candidates themselves.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Ray conducted a tour of ten counties in the company of U.S.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Blake, addressing crowds in Brookville, Lawrenceburg and Vincennes.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Ray's incumbency was an asset to his campaign, as he was better known to the public than either Canby or Moore, who could not rival the governor's long-established reputation.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] In June the pro-Adams editor of the Brookville *Repository*, Augustus Jocelyn, published an interview with Ray that dealt a severe blow to the governor's budding alliance with the Jacksonians.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Jocelyn quoted Ray as denying the 1824 presidential election had been stolen from Jackson and denouncing the Jackson party as "an outrageous and violent faction" which it was "the duty of every good man" to oppose.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] In response, the Jackson State Committee cut all ties with Ray and published in full their previous correspondence, and Canby, his private business now concluded, re-emerged as a candidate for governor.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] His alliance with the Jackson party had been only prospective, in the event the Adams faction were to mount a partisan campaign against him; as for his description of Jacksonians as "outrageous and violent," Ray said, the remark was entirely Jocelyn's invention.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Ray defeated his two opponents less than 40% of the statewide vote, polling strongest in the counties of the Whitewater Valley.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Canby's support came mostly from southern counties that would go on to favor Jackson in the October presidential election, as well as Terre Haute, while Moore carried a total of nine counties along the periphery of the state.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] The relationship between presidential party identity and voter behavior in the gubernatorial election is ambiguous.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Carmony writes that while the election results show some degree of correlation between presidential preference and gubernatorial politics, "local and personal preferences remained strong." Ray carried thirty-two counties, winning votes from both Jacksonians and Anti-Jacksonians in equal numbers.
[src:1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election/1828-indiana-gubernatorial-election] Despite this, he became the first governor to be elected with less than a majority of the votes.
